<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">
Therophyte (summer-annual). Up to 1 m. Stem terete or angular, striped with green, sometimes red especially in the axils, hard, erect to ascending, branched mainly in the basal part; lowermost branches ascending from an almost horizontal base, long. Leaves with petiole about half as long as the blade; blade ovate to broadly ovate or elliptic, often with almost parallel margins in the middle part, slightly tapering towards the apex, 2-5 x 1-2.5 cm, dark olive-green to bluish green above, beneath often more bluish, sometimes bordered with red; apex obtuse; margin usually 
<normalizedToken originalValue="±" pageId="19" pageNumber="23">+/-</normalizedToken>
regularly dentate with small teeth (basalmost teeth sometimes slightly larger than the others) or sometimes entire. Bracts with narrowly trullate to narrowly elliptic blade; margin entire.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">Inflorescences usually terminal and with few spike-like branches, usually ebracteate; glomerules small. Flowers bisexual or female. Tepals 5, olive-green, connate at base, weakly keeled. Stamens 5. Stigmas 2. Nut falling with the perianth; pericarp easily detached. Seed horizontal, broadly ovate in outline (ratio length/width 1.06-1.17), 1-1.2 mm; edge slightly keeled; seed-coat black, smooth or sometimes with faint radial striae. - Late summer to late autumn.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">[2n=36]</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">Distribution. For Norden, see the subspecies.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">C and E Europe; SW and C Asia, India; N North America.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="discussion">
<paragraph lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="25" pageId="19" pageNumber="23" type="mainText">
Variation. According to many chromosome counts from populations in various parts of its area, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="74" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="19" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">C. strictum</taxonomicName>
is a tetraploid with 2n=36. It is fairly variable, even though some related taxa have been separated, e.g. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="19" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="striatiforme">C. striatiforme</taxonomicName>
(17) and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="19" pageNumber="23" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virgatum">C. virgatum</taxonomicName>
(rare casual), and 
<pageBreakToken pageId="21" pageNumber="25" start="start">the</pageBreakToken>
two subspecies recognized here do not cover the entire morphological variation. - The status of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virgatum" subspecies="glaucophyllum">subsp. glaucophyllum</taxonomicName>
needs to be clarified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="25" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="21" pageNumber="25" type="mainText">
Similar taxa. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">Chenopodium strictum</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.bestMatchDistance="2359" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">C. album</taxonomicName>
(15), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="missouriense">C. missouriense</taxonomicName>
(16), 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="striatiforme">C striatiforme</taxonomicName>
(17) and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="virgatum">C virgatum</taxonomicName>
(rare casual). 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">C strictum</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">C album</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="missouriense">C missouriense</taxonomicName>
in having leaf-blades which are more elliptic and entire or dentate with teeth more equal in size. The olive-green or bluish leaf colour of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">C strictum</taxonomicName>
is also diagnostic. The seeds of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">C strictum</taxonomicName>
are smaller and more ovate in outline than those of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">C album</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="striatiforme">C striatiforme</taxonomicName>
is smaller and more delicate, and its leaves are smaller and of a different shape. The inflorescences of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Chenopodium" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="21" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strictum">C strictum</taxonomicName>
are usually spike-like, and the leaves are olive-green or bluish green.
</paragraph>
